<TITLE> Indian troops kill four militants in Kashmir </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 SRINAGAR, India, Mar 27, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Indian troops shot dead four separatist militants on Thursday in Kashmir, the army and police said, a day after the Pakistan-based Lashkar-e-Taiba (LeT) militant group threatened more attacks in the region. While two militants were killed as they tried to infiltrate into Indian Kashmir, troops shot dead two others, including a senior LeT commander in a separate firefight, officials said. This week, at least 25 people -- eight of them soldiers -- have been killed in Kashmir as LeT militants, blamed for November's Mumbai attacks, battled the army in dense forest. Security officials said Thursday's incursion took place in north Kashmir's Gurez sector on the Line of Control (LoC), a military line which divides Kashmir between India and Pakistan. "Fierce encounter started when security forces came face-to-face with a group of militants who tried to infiltrate from the other side of LoC," a police spokesman said. The second firefight involving the LeT commander took place near a remote village in northern Kashmir. Indian authorities say a large number of Islamist militants might try to infiltrate into the Indian side of Kashmir, ahead of the April/May parliamentary election. Tens of thousands of people have been killed since an anti-India insurgency broke out in Kashmir in 1989. But officials say overall violence has declined in Kashmir since India and Pakistan, who claim the region in full and have fought two wars over it, began a slow-moving peace process in 2004. New Delhi paused that dialogue after the Mumbai att
